[[sn:Rikkokushi]] [[en:Rikkokushi]]
[[Category:Pages without translation templates]] <!--enwiki derived wikidata interwikis--> [[cs:Rikkokuši]] [[de:Rikkokushi]] [[es:Rikkokushi]] [[eu:Rikkokushi]] [[fa:شش تاریخ ملی]] [[fr:Rikkokushi]] [[it:Rikkokushi]] [[ja:六国史]] [[ko:육국사]] [[pt:Rikkokushi]] [[ru:Риккокуси]] [[simple:Rikkokushi]] [[zh:六國史]] [[Category:Pages with valid en interwikis]] [[Category:pages with valid en interwikis 2]]

{{Italic title|reason=}} {{Nihongo|'''''Rikkokushi'''''|六国史|}} is a general term for Japan's '''Six National Histories''' chronicling the mythology and history of Japan from the earliest times to 887.<ref>Kōdansha (1983)</ref> The six histories were written at the imperial court during the 8th and 9th centuries, under order of the Emperors.<ref>Sakamoto (1991)</ref> The basic sources were the court records kept by the Ministry of Central Imperial Affairs, and the biographies of meritorious officials composed in the Ministry of Ceremonial Affairs.<ref>Kōdansha (1983)</ref>
The collection consists of the following texts: *''[[Nihon Shoki]]'' (Chronicle of Japan; also called ''Nihongi'') – 30 volumes covering the mythological period through 697. Completed by [[Toneri Shinnō]] in 720. *''[[Shoku Nihongi]]'' (Chronicle of Japan, Continued; also called ''Shokki'') – 40 volumes covering 697 through 791. Completed by [[:en:Fujiwara no Tsugutada|Fujiwara no Tsugutada]] and [[Sugano no Mamichi]] in 797. *''[[Nihon Kōki]]'' (Later Chronicle of Japan) – 40 volumes covering 792 through 833. Completed by [[:en:Fujiwara no Fuyutsugu|Fujiwara no Fuyutsugu]] and [[:en:Fujiwara no Otsugu|Fujiwara no Otsugu]] in 840. *''[[Shoku Nihon Kōki]]'' (Later Chronicle of Japan, Continued) – 20 volumes covering 833 through 850. Completed by [[:en:Fujiwara no Yoshifusa|Fujiwara no Yoshifusa]], [[:en:Fujiwara no Yoshimi|Fujiwara no Yoshimi]], [[Tomo no Yoshio]], and [[Haruzumi no Yoshitada]] in 869. *''[[Nihon Montoku Tennō Jitsuroku]]'' (Veritable Record of Emperor Montoku of Japan; also called ''Montoku jitsuroku'') – 10 volumes covering 850 through 858. Completed by [[:en:Fujiwara no Mototsune|Fujiwara no Mototsune]] and [[Sugawara no Koreyoshi]] in 879. *''[[Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku]]'' (Veritable Record of Three Generations [of Emperors] of Japan; also called ''Sandai jitsuroku'') – 50 volumes covering 858 through 887. Completed by [[:en:Fujiwara no Tokihira|Fujiwara no Tokihira]] and [[Ōkura no Yoshiyuki]] in 901.
The national histories were discontinued after the ''Sandai Jitsuroku''; they were followed by the [[Shikyō|four Mirror books]] (starting with ''[[:en:Ōkagami|Ōkagami]]'').
==See also== *''[[Ruijū Kokushi]]'', a categorized and chronological history text of the ''Six National Histories'' *[[Historiography of Japan]]
