The collection consists of the following texts: *''[[Nihon Shoki]]'' (Chronicle of Japan; also called ''Nihongi'') – 30 volumes covering the mythological period through 697. Completed by [[Toneri Shinnō]] in 720. *''[[Shoku Nihongi]]'' (Chronicle of Japan, Continued; also called ''Shokki'') – 40 volumes covering 697 through 791. Completed by [[:en:Fujiwara no Tsugutada|Fujiwara no Tsugutada]] and [[:en:Sugano no Mamichi|Sugano no Mamichi]] in 797. *''[[:en:Nihon Kōki|Nihon Kōki]]'' (Later Chronicle of Japan) – 40 volumes covering 792 through 833. Completed by [[:en:Fujiwara no Fuyutsugu|Fujiwara no Fuyutsugu]] and [[:en:Fujiwara no Otsugu|Fujiwara no Otsugu]] in 840. *''[[Shoku Nihon Kōki]]'' (Later Chronicle of Japan, Continued) – 20 volumes covering 833 through 850. Completed by [[:en:Fujiwara no Yoshifusa|Fujiwara no Yoshifusa]], [[:en:Fujiwara no Yoshimi|Fujiwara no Yoshimi]], [[Tomo no Yoshio]], and [[Haruzumi no Yoshitada]] in 869. *''[[Nihon Montoku Tennō Jitsuroku]]'' (Veritable Record of Emperor Montoku of Japan; also called ''Montoku jitsuroku'') – 10 volumes covering 850 through 858. Completed by [[:en:Fujiwara no Mototsune|Fujiwara no Mototsune]] and [[:en:Sugawara no Koreyoshi|Sugawara no Koreyoshi]] in 879. *''[[Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku]]'' (Veritable Record of Three Generations [of Emperors] of Japan; also called ''Sandai jitsuroku'') – 50 volumes covering 858 through 887. Completed by [[:en:Fujiwara no Tokihira|Fujiwara no Tokihira]] and [[Ōkura no Yoshiyuki]] in 901.
The national histories were discontinued after the ''Sandai Jitsuroku''; they were followed by the [[:en:Shikyō|four Mirror books]] (starting with ''[[:en:Ōkagami|Ōkagami]]'').
==See also== *''[[Ruijū Kokushi]]'', a categorized and chronological history text of the ''Six National Histories'' *[[:en:Historiography of Japan|Historiography of Japan]]
